               <p>ELIZABETH HOUNSLOW. I am the wife of 
               <persName id="t18310908-266-person1938">
                  John 
                  Hounslow
               <interp inst="t18310908-266-person1938" type="surname" value="Hounslow"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-266-person1938" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-266-person1938" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             - he is a <rs id="t18310908-266-viclabel1360" type="occupation">bootman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-266-victim1937 t18310908-266-viclabel1360"></join>; the prisoner worked for a Mr. Collins, of the Old Jewry, and used to lodged with us. On the 9th of July he breakfasted with us, and when he had gone about ten minutes we missed these tools - I followed him, and just as I came to St. Paul's, he said, "By G - d, here she is;" I took hold of his arm - he wrenched himself from me, and ran up a court, which was no thoroughfare, where I caught him - he said he had nothing; at last he took three pieces of those articles out of his pocket, and said he had no more; when the officer came he found this fourth piece.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I took the tools for a debt which a man owed me.</p>
